a:1:{i:0;a:2:{s:5:"title";s:27:"Pet Safety - Micro-chipping";s:7:"content";s:1029:"Micro-chipping your pet is one of the most secure ways to keep them safe and ensure they can be returned to you if they go missing. While collars and identification tags are convenient, they can be removed or lost relatively easily. A microchip, on the other hand, is a permanent form of identification that stays with your pet throughout their life.

The microchip itself is tiny - about the same size as a grain of rice - and is inserted under the skin between the shoulder blades using a hypodermic needle. The procedure is quick and simple, similar to a routine vaccination. Most dogs feel discomfort for no more than a few seconds during the insertion. After insertion, it's important to check the chip occasionally to ensure it's still working properly.

The risk of infection from microchipping is very low, but owners should monitor the insertion site for the first few days to make sure the area does not become infected or inflamed. If any redness, swelling, or discharge appears, contact your veterinarian immediately.";}}
